{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure boundary is real filesystem watch behavior (recursive subscription and event delivery from OS). A mocked watcher can falsely pass even if real OS events from nested paths are never emitted or never mapped correctly.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temp directory tree, create a nested subdirectory under the watched root, write a file into that subdirectory, and assert the transformed output appears in the output directory. Verify the daemon remains running and no manual reconfiguration/restart is needed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is primarily module handoff/state behavior (event intake + dedup cache/window + enqueue/processor), not OS-specific by itself. A unit test of only a helper function may miss cache lifecycle/config wiring bugs; wiring-level test is the minimum realistic boundary.","test_description":"Instantiate the daemon pipeline components with real in-process dependencies (no OS watcher), configure dedup window, submit two processing requests for the same canonical path within the window, and assert only one pipeline execution occurs. Advance time beyond the window and assert a new request is accepted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The bug appears at the OS event boundary: duplicate/close/write/rename event bursts differ by platform and watcher backend. Mocking event streams can hide real coalescing/race behavior.","test_description":"Run the daemon with a real watched directory and perform a write pattern known to trigger multiple FS events (e.g., temp-write + rename or chunked writes). Capture processing count for that file and assert exactly one completed transformation/output artifact.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Directory deletion/recreation rebind behavior depends on OS watcher semantics and resource lifecycle. In-memory mocks typically do not reproduce invalidated watch handles and re-subscription races.","test_description":"Start daemon watching a real directory, delete the watched directory while daemon is live, recreate it at the same path, then add a new file. Assert the new file is processed successfully without restarting the process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.97,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Ordering depends on real filesystem metadata/timestamp precision plus intake ordering under concurrent arrivals. Pure module tests can miss real timestamp resolution/tie behavior and stat timing quirks.","test_description":"With daemon running on a real directory, create multiple files in rapid succession/concurrently, record their creation timestamps as observed by the daemon’s metadata lookup, and assert processing order matches timestamp order (with an explicit deterministic tie-break rule if equal).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This failure is about real write-in-progress timing, file locks/size stabilization, and watcher event timing from OS/subprocess I/O. Mocked timing usually masks premature pickup races.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real watched directory, begin writing a large file in chunks from a separate process/stream while keeping it open, trigger arrival event naturally, and assert no processing/output occurs until the writer closes and file is complete; then assert exactly one successful processing run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
